%%TITLE
Human papilloma virus (HPV) infection leads to the development of head and neck lesions but offers better prognosis in malignant Indian patients.
%%ABSTRACT
Head and neck cancers constitute a multifactorial global disease burden and are associated with human papilloma virus (HPV) as a possible risk factor. The aim of the study is to understand the relationship between HPV and the development of head and neck lesions in Indian patients. To this end, frequency of HPV was assessed in relation to different demographic and etiological features and correlated with patient survival. The prevalence of HPV significantly increased from mild dysplastic lesions (43.6%) to head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC) stage IV (68.5%) with HPV 16 being pre-dominant in both dysplasia (43.8%) and HNSCC (61.5%). Similar trend was observed in increasing grades of the tumour. In invasive lesions, patients aged below the median age of onset showed significantly higher occurrence of HPV than those above it. Patients harbouring HPV showed a significantly better survival irrespective of age of onset. Likewise, better survival was observed in tobacco habit negative/HPV-positive patients, and as reflected in both univariate and multivariate analysis. Majority of the HPV 16-positive samples showed moderate/high nuclear expression of HPV E6 and E7 proteins in tumours and respective basal layer of adjacent normal tissues. Thus, our data indicate that frequent HPV infection, along with tobacco habit, is a pre-requisite factor for the development of HNSCC of Indian patients but offers a better survival even during tobacco usage, implicating its diagnostic and prognostic importance.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Study protocol
The study included 598 patients who had visited the out- patient departments at Chittaranjan National Cancer Insti- tute, Kolkata and Dr. R. Ahmed Dental College, Kolkata,
for biopsy and/or surgery. Eligibility criteria were patho- logically confirmed, untreated, pre-malignant or squamous cell carcinomas of the head and neck with patients present- ing satisfactory hepatic, renal and bone marrow functions. Relevant clinical history including lifetime exposure to tobacco and primary site (WHO classification) and written informed consent was obtained from the patients, as well as the hospital authorities and institutional ethical committee prior to the study. From 1996 to 2011, 598 patients who had enrolled for the study and had fulfilled the eligibility criteria were assessed for HPV status. Details about the patients are presented in Table , including the number of patients presenting with different tumour sites.
Detection and typing of high‑risk HPV
The presence of HPV in the head and neck lesions was detected by PCR using MY09 and MY11 primers, designed from the consensus L1 region of the virus []. L1-posi- tive samples were typed for high-risk HPV 16 and HPV 18 using type-specific primers, designed from the E6 region of HPV16 and LCR region of HPV18. Primer details in Supplementary Table 1. Final confirmation of HPV sub- types was performed by Southern hybridization. In brief, the PCR products, after gel electrophoresis were dry trans- ferred to Gene screen nylon membrane. The membranes were pre-hybridized with a mixture of 2X SSC, 1% SDS, 10% dextran sulphate and 50% deionized formamide and hybridized with [αP32] dCTP (108cpm/μg) labelled HPV16/ HPV 18 type-specific probes for 24 h. Membranes were subsequently washed with 2× SSC/15 min at room temper- ature, followed by 2× SSC + 1% SDS for 20 min twice and 0.2× SSC + 1% SDS for 20 min twice at 42 °C. Hybridized membranes were exposed to X-ray films with intensifier screens at −80 °C/7–8 days. SiHa DNA was used as HPV 16-positive control.
Immunohistochemical expression
Analyses for the expression of HPV 16 oncoproteins E6 and E7 were performed in 72 tumours and adjacent nor- mal epithelium according to the standard protocol []. In brief, 4–5 µm of paraffin sections were deparaffinised, serially hydrated and antigens retrieved using Citrate buffer (pH 6.0) at 65 °C/30 min. The sections were blocked using 5% BSA/30 min at room temperature and incubated with primary antibodies E6 (sc-1584) and E7 (sc-6981) from Santa Cruz Biotechnology, CA, at a dilution of 1:100 at 4 °C/overnight. Secondary antibody was used in a dilution of 1:500 and DAB used as the chromogen with slides pho- tographed under a bright-field microscope (Leica DM1000, Germany). Expression of tumours was compared by considering the expression of the proteins in the basal layer of the non-malignant adjacent normal as the standard.
Study end point
The end point selected was an overall survival (recurrence or disease free) of 5 years, or the time from randomization to death. Data were censored either if the patient was lost in follow-up or was alive till the end point.
Statistical analysis
Estimation of risk associated with HPV infection and demographic features was determined by Odds Ratio through univariate analysis using Fisher’s exact test. Multivariate analysis using Cox proportional hazard regression model calculated the Hazard Ratio for risk of HPV in conjunction with all clinico-pathological parameters. Chi-square test for trend detected the linear variation with subsequent stages and grades of lesions. Disease- or recurrence-free survival was calculated by Log-Rank test in relation to the presence or absence of variables and survival plotted using Kaplan–Meier anal- ysis []. All tests were two tailed, with a Confidence Interval (CI) of 95% and probability (p) value <0.05 being considered significant. All calculations were by softwares Epi Info 7 (CDC, Atlanta) and IBM SPSS 21 (SPSS, Chicago, IL). Artwork was created with the help of Photoshop CS6 (Adobe, CA).
Results
Demographic features of patients presenting with head and neck lesions
Patients were predominantly male (76.1%), presented with lesions in the oral cavity (88.5%) and were habitual tobacco users (63.4%). Patients who harboured dysplastic lesions (N = 162) had a median age of 48 ± 12.4, while the rest presented malignant squamous cell carcinoma (median age 52 ± 14).
Prevalence of HPV significantly increased
from dysplasia to invasive squamous cell carcinoma
The presence of HPV was detected in 48.8% (79/162) of the dysplastic lesions screened, followed by a significant (p = 0.001) increase in the prevalence of HNSCC, 63.3% (278/436) (Fig. a–d). Among the HPV-positive samples, the presence of HPV 16 and 18 were 89.9, 10.1% in dys- plastic lesions and 96.4, 6.8% in HNSCC, respectively

In dysplastic lesions, while there was similar distribution of HPV-positive patients irrespective of tobacco habit (T− and T+ groups), HNSCC patients showed a significantly higher prevalence of HPV-positive patients with both the presence and absence of tobacco habit. (Fig. c). Co-infection of HPV 16/18 was 1.3% in dysplas- tic lesions and 2.9% in HNSCC (Fig. c). HPV prevalence increased significantly (p = 0.001) during progression from dysplasia to invasive lesions (Fig. d). HPV also increased significantly with enhancing grades of the invasive tumours (Table ).
Patients with lower age of onset of HNSCC showed a greater prevalence of HPV
HPV prevalence detected in the different sites of head and neck lesions was comparable (Table ). Comparable fre- quency of HPV prevalence was also observed in both males and females in the head and neck lesions (Table ). While there was similar distribution of HPV-positive patients above or below the median age of onset in dysplastic lesions, there was a significantly higher number of HPV- positive patients below the median age of onset in HNSCC (Table ). Concurrent consideration of tobacco usage (T) and HPV infection (H) revealed a disparate distribution of patients into four etiological groups, with significantly higher prevalence of HNSCC patients harbouring HPV irrespective of tobacco habit, although no such correla- tion was observed in patients harbouring dysplastic lesions (Fig. e).
HPV‑positive HNSCC patients had a significantly enhanced overall and recurrence‑free survival compared to HPV‑negative cases
Assessment of 5-year overall disease- and recurrence-free survival in HNSCC patients by Kaplan–Meier analysis indicated that HPV-positive patients showed significantly better survival (p = 0.03) than those negative for HPV (Fig. a). Males harbouring HPV-positive tumours showed significantly better survival (p = 0.005) than HPV-negative males (Fig. b). Patients both above and below the median age showed comparatively superior survival in HPV-posi- tive cases than in the absence of HPV (Fig. c, d). Tobacco users in contrast had a significantly poor survival compared to non-users (data not shown).
Simultaneous consideration of the combina- torial effects of tobacco and HPV indicated dif- ferential survival in different patient groups in the following order: T−H+ (85.2%) > T+H+ (78.4%) > T−H− (76.4%) > T+H− (58.4%) (Fig. e, f).
Thus, patients harbouring HPV, despite the presence of tobacco habit (T + H+) show a better survival than those who lacked both factors (T−H−) or only tobacco usage (T+H−), indicating its prognostic importance.
Considering the entire cohort in univariate analysis, age, gender and HPV prevalence were considered as sig- nificant risk factors in the development of the disease,
i.e. HPV-negative female patients with a greater age have a poor overall survival (Table a). In stratification of the data of HPV-negative patients only, it was evident that higher stage and grade of the patients presented an inferior survival (Table b, c), although no such association was observed in HPV-positive cases. Similarly, multivariate analysis indicated the importance of higher grade, stage and the absence of HPV in the entire cohort as determinants of poor survival, with progressive grade and stage offering a dismal overall survival in HPV-negative cases (Table d–f). As previously observed, no such association was observed in HPV-positive patients. Thus, HPV-positive patients had a better overall survival compared to their HPV-negative counterparts, irrespective of poor clinico-pathological parameters presented.
HPV oncoproteins were predominantly expressed in the nucleus of proliferative cells
Expression of HPV 16 proteins were validated in 72 normal and paired tumours, out of which 56 pairs were determined HPV 16 positive by PCR/Southern hybridization (Supple- mentary Table 2). For E7, moderate/high expression of the protein was detected in the basal layer of normal tissues in 67.9% (38/56) samples (Fig. a, c, Supplementary Table 2). Comparable nuclear expression was also observed in the paired tumour tissues. Likewise, moderate/high nuclear expression of E6 was detected in the basal layer of the normal epithelial tissues in 78.6% (42/56) samples, with similar expression in the adjacent tumour tissues samples (Fig. a, c, Supplementary Table 2). Significant concord- ance was observed between the presence of HPV 16 and expression of its oncoproteins in normal/paired tumours (Supplementary Table 2).
